Diagnosis.
This species belongs to the 

kinabaluensis

-group based on the following characters: carapace wedge-shaped with undulating lateral margins; posterior end of carapace not produced into an elongated stalk (

); PER recurved and much longer than AER (

); palpal tegulum not enlarged and bulbous (

). Males of this species have a similar cephalothorax and abdomen to those of 

U. trisula

               sp. nov.

, but can be distinguished from it (as well as from all other congeners) by the long bifid shape of the RTA (

), each lobe curving in the opposite direction of one another, the ventral lobe additionally with a small spine-like dorsal projection (

) (versus trifid in 

U. trisula

, 

). Female: unknown

